  "game_explanation": "This game is likely to revolve around the strong asymmetry in private values for BLUE and RED. Buffalo highly values BLUE and dislikes RED, so Buffalo's natural incentive is to give up RED or possibly GREEN in order to acquire BLUE. Bear values both BLUE and RED, with BLUE especially valuable, so Bear is a demanding counterparty: Bear will usually avoid giving away BLUE unless the compensation is very attractive, but Bear is a willing buyer of RED from either other player because Bear values RED much more than they likely do. Goose values GREEN at the common $0.50 and values both RED and BLUE very little, so Goose is the most likely sink for low-value colors and the most willing accepter of trades that convert RED or BLUE into GREEN. Because players only know their own values, proposals must be based on inference from acceptances and inventory changes rather than direct knowledge of who values what. Early-round uncertainty should produce some exploratory offers. Over time, accepted trades should reveal that Goose is comparatively easy to trade with and that Bear is hard to induce to part with BLUE. Buffalo's high reflection and tolerance for unequal outcomes make targeted, self-beneficial offers likely; Bear's mixed cooperative signals but moderate responder standards suggest selective acceptance of clearly profitable trades; Goose's low rejection threshold and low values for RED/BLUE suggest willingness to accept many positive-surplus offers. The main uncertainty is whether proposers risk aggressive offers to test counterparties or instead make modest proposals likely to be accepted. A plausible full-game path is that Buffalo repeatedly tries to turn low-value RED into BLUE, Bear trades away some GREEN to collect RED, and Goose accepts deals that swap low-value RED/BLUE for GREEN or occasionally for small amounts of the other low-value color when profitable.",
