  "game_explanation": "This game should center on red-blue exchange rather than green. Green is worth $0.50 to everyone, so it creates little speculative advantage and mainly serves as a neutral payment chip. By contrast, red and blue have strong cross-player differences: badger values RED and BLUE equally highly at $0.80 each, camel values RED more than BLUE ($0.60 vs $0.40), and squid values BLUE much more than RED ($0.60 vs $0.20). That means camel is the natural demander of RED, squid is the natural demander of BLUE, and badger is relatively flexible because both private colors are highly valuable to him. From an efficiency perspective, RED should tend to move away from squid and toward camel or badger, while BLUE should tend to move away from camel and toward badger or squid. The strategic complication is that players do not know one another's values; they only see whether a posted trade is privately profitable for themselves. So proposals are likely to start somewhat exploratory, with players using simple ratios that are clearly favorable from their own side while hoping at least one counterpart also benefits. The acceptance environment is also noisy because two counterparties can both accept a trade, in which case the final recipient is random. Given the personas, camel and squid seem relatively tolerant responders and less likely to reject profitable but uneven trades, while badger looks somewhat more balanced and adaptive. Overall, the most likely full-game path is a sequence of modest, positive-surplus red-blue trades, with occasional declined offers when a proposer asks for too much of the color they most want.",
